<paragraph blockId="3.[211,1172,556,708]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">
<emphasis box="[211,420,557,581]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Dorsal chaetotaxy.</emphasis>
Macrochaetotaxy as in 
<figureCitation box="[692,815,556,580]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[143,210,1674,1696]" captionTargetBox="[162,1083,161,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-5@4.[162,1084,161,1641]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Labrum; (B) mandible; (C) maxillary head (1–6: lamella 1–6); (D) maxillary outer lobe; (E) hypostomal setae in labial pulp; (F) dorsal cephalic macrochaetotaxy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631143/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figures 2F</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[872,910,556,580]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[211,278,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[225,1159,163,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@5.[225,1159,162,1695]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Dorsal tergal macrochaetotaxy; (B) trochanteral organ; (C) spiny inner setae on hind tibiotarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631145/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">3A</figureCitation>
. Dorsal head with two, four anterior and two posterior macrochaetae; 4 + 4 posterior marginal setae arranged in a loose row (
<figureCitation box="[401,523,620,644]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[143,210,1674,1696]" captionTargetBox="[162,1083,161,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-5@4.[162,1084,161,1641]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Labrum; (B) mandible; (C) maxillary head (1–6: lamella 1–6); (D) maxillary outer lobe; (E) hypostomal setae in labial pulp; (F) dorsal cephalic macrochaetotaxy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631143/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 2F</figureCitation>
). Macrochaetae on each tergum with one to six guard microchaetae and bothriotricha without those accessory setae around it. Abd. IV without anterior macrochaeta (
<figureCitation box="[562,681,684,708]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[211,278,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[225,1159,163,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@5.[225,1159,162,1695]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Dorsal tergal macrochaetotaxy; (B) trochanteral organ; (C) spiny inner setae on hind tibiotarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631145/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 3A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[211,1172,754,970]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">
<emphasis box="[211,271,756,779]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Legs.</emphasis>
Trochanteral organ reduced to one, one slender spiny seta; some shorter smooth spiny setae present over a distance around trochanteral organ, sockets of them rounded and big as those of setae on trochanteral organ (
<figureCitation box="[778,897,818,842]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[211,278,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[225,1159,163,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@5.[225,1159,162,1695]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Dorsal tergal macrochaetotaxy; (B) trochanteral organ; (C) spiny inner setae on hind tibiotarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631145/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
). Tibiotarsus with zero, zero, two blunt spiny inner setae (
<figureCitation box="[608,730,850,874]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[211,278,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[225,1159,163,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@5.[225,1159,162,1695]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Dorsal tergal macrochaetotaxy; (B) trochanteral organ; (C) spiny inner setae on hind tibiotarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631145" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631145/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 3C</figureCitation>
). Tenent hair apically spatulate, much shorter than inner side of unguis. Unguis relatively straight, curved only at tips, with four, four, four inner teeth and a pair of pseudonychia. Unguiculus about two-thirds the length of unguis and with one inner tooth (
<figureCitation box="[736,856,946,970]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[143,210,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[198,1050,161,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@6.[198,1050,161,1694]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Claw; (B) tenaculum; (C) dental spines; (D) mucro." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631149/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 4A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[211,1172,1016,1423]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">
<emphasis box="[211,473,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Abdominal appendages.</emphasis>
Ventral tube covered by scales and setae both anteriorly and posteriorly; each side of anterior face with about 40 setae in different sizes, three of which larger than others. Tenaculum with 4 + 4 teeth, corpus unscaled and with one seta shorter than rami (
<figureCitation box="[532,650,1112,1136]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[143,210,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[198,1050,161,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@6.[198,1050,161,1694]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Claw; (B) tenaculum; (C) dental spines; (D) mucro." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631149/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 4B</figureCitation>
). Furcula ratio as 4.3–5.0: 5.3–6.6: 1.0 from manubrium to mucro. Manubrium with lateral row of 11–13 large blunt setae, both dorsal and ventral face scaled and no distinct “principal setae” appearing on dorsal face. Inner bases of dentes bearing a pair of large pointed scales with a few striate sculptures on surface. Dental spine formula as II 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,799,1240,1264]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">/</emphasis>
7–10, II. Spines all simple, with irregular longitudinal streaks, basal pair on medial dental parts distinctly smaller than others (
<figureCitation box="[296,413,1303,1327]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[143,210,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[198,1050,161,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-5@6.[198,1050,161,1694]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Pogonognathellus heterochros sp. nov. (A) Claw; (B) tenaculum; (C) dental spines; (D) mucro." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4631149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4631149/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">Figure 4C</figureCitation>
). Mucro elongate, basal two teeth close to each other, distance from base of mucro to inner basal tooth about 1 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[712,724,1335,1359]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1245">/</emphasis>
